// Conspiracy theories: individual myths with refutations, tags, categories, sources (HASHEM defined above)
const CONSPIRACIES = [
  { slug: 'khazar-myth', title: 'The Jews Of Today Aren\'t The Real Jews, They\'re Khazars!', summary: 'The "Khazar hypothesis" claims modern Jews descend from converts, not ancient Israelites. It is used to deny Jewish indigeneity and legitimacy.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The Khazar theory emerged in the 19th and early 20th centuries. It claimed that Ashkenazi Jews descended mainly from the Khazars, a Turkic people whose rulers supposedly converted to Judaism in the medieval period. The idea was later popularized in books and online to argue that modern Jews are "impostors" with no ancestral tie to the Land of Israel.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Antisemites use the Khazar myth to deny Jewish indigeneity and legitimacy. If "today\'s Jews" are Khazar converts rather than Israelites, the argument goes, they have no historical claim to the land and Israel is a "colonial" fraud. The theory also fuels the idea that Jews are a "fake" or "invented" people. It serves the geopolitical and religious goal of some Islamic regimes and movements to wipe Israel off the map by denying Jewish ties to the land. State and non-state actors (e.g., Iran, Russia) have also promoted such narratives to divide Americans from their ally Israel and to turn the West against itself.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Genetic and historical research has thoroughly debunked the Khazar-origin thesis. Ashkenazi Jews show substantial Levantine and Middle Eastern ancestry consistent with ancient Israelite and diaspora history. Jewish continuity in the land and across the diaspora is well documented. The Khazar kingdom did have a period of royal conversion, but there is no evidence that Ashkenazi Jewry descends mainly from Khazars. The theory is a pseudoscientific canard used to delegitimize Jews and Israel.</p>', category: 'Jewish identity & history', tags: ['Khazars', 'Jewish identity', 'antisemitic canard'], sort_order: 1, sources: [{ label: 'Hashem.Faith – Jewish identity', url: `${HASHEM}/` }] },
  { slug: 'jesus-boiling-hell', title: 'The Jews Hate Jesus And Believe He\'s Boiling In Excrement In Hell', summary: 'A vicious antisemitic libel that distorts Talmudic and Jewish tradition about Jesus and the afterlife.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Medieval Christian polemics and later antisemitic literature claimed that the Talmud describes Jesus suffering in hell, often in grotesque and scatological terms. These claims relied on mistranslations, out-of-context passages, or outright forgeries. The libel was used to justify violence and persecution of Jews for centuries.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth is spread to portray Jews as hateful of Christianity and of Jesus, and to suggest that Jewish texts are inherently hostile or obscene. It is used to incite hatred and to justify discrimination or violence against Jews. Throughout history, Christian authorities used such libels to justify forced conversion, expulsion, and pogroms; today, some Christian nationalists still traffic in these tropes, with a minority openly desiring the removal or conversion of Jews in America and elsewhere.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Jewish texts do not teach that Jesus (or any person) is "boiling in excrement" in hell. The Talmud is a vast legal and narrative corpus; isolated lines are often misattributed, mistranslated, or from debated passages. No mainstream Jewish tradition teaches the grotesque image antisemites attribute to it. The claim is a classic libel. <a href="https://hashem.faith/did-the-jews-kill-jesus/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Hashem.Faith</a> addresses the Jesus narrative and Christianity in the Talmud with primary-source context.</p>', category: 'Jewish beliefs', tags: ['Jesus', 'Talmud', 'blood libel', 'Christian antisemitism'], sort_order: 2, sources: [{ label: 'Did the Jews kill Jesus?', url: `${HASHEM}/did-the-jews-kill-jesus/` }, { label: 'Christianity in the Talmud', url: `${HASHEM}/christianity-in-the-talmud/` }] },
  { slug: 'child-sacrifice-blood-libel', title: 'The Jews Believe In Child Sacrifice', summary: 'The blood libel: the false accusation that Jews use Christian (or other) children\'s blood in rituals.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The blood libel—the accusation that Jews murder non-Jewish children and use their blood in religious rituals—dates to the Middle Ages. It has appeared across Europe and elsewhere, often around Passover, and has repeatedly led to pogroms, trials, and murders. Despite papal and secular repudiations, the libel has been revived in antisemitic propaganda into the modern era.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Antisemites use the blood libel to portray Jews as evil, ritualistic killers and to justify violence against them. It is a defining example of conspiracy thinking: a secret, murderous practice attributed to an entire group with no evidence. Historically it was central to Christian persecution of Jews (expulsions, massacres, forced conversion). In the modern era it has been revived by some Christian nationalist circles and by foreign-backed disinformation (e.g., from Russia or Iran) aimed at dividing Western societies and turning people against Jewish communities and Israel.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>The blood libel is completely false. No Jewish law or tradition permits or condones murder, child sacrifice, or the use of human blood in ritual. Jewish dietary law strictly forbids the consumption of blood. The accusation has been debunked by scholars, courts, and religious authorities countless times. It has caused immense suffering and remains a dangerous antisemitic myth.</p>', category: 'Jewish beliefs', tags: ['blood libel', 'child sacrifice', 'ritual murder'], sort_order: 3, sources: [{ label: 'Hashem.Faith', url: `${HASHEM}/` }] },
  { slug: 'non-jews-lesser', title: 'The Jews View Non-Jews As Lesser Beings', summary: 'The claim that Jewish texts or tradition teach that gentiles are inferior or subhuman.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Antisemites have long claimed that the Talmud or other Jewish texts teach that non-Jews (gentiles) are inferior, subhuman, or "animals." These claims rely on pulling isolated phrases out of context, mistranslating ancient legal or rhetorical passages, or citing forgeries. The same tropes have been used to justify discrimination and violence.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth is used to portray Judaism as inherently hateful and to suggest that Jews view everyone else as lesser. It fuels the idea that Jews are a hostile, supremacist group and that "Jewish texts" justify mistreatment of non-Jews. It has a long history in Christian polemics used to justify discrimination, forced conversion, or violence. Today it is amplified by some Christian nationalists and by foreign actors (Iran, Russia, Qatar, China) seeking to divide Americans and undermine support for Israel and for Jewish participation in public life.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Jewish tradition does not teach that non-Jews are lesser or subhuman. The Talmud and later authorities recognize the dignity of all people; the Noahide laws apply to all humanity and assume moral responsibility for everyone. Antisemites quote-mine and mistranslate complex legal or aggadic passages to suggest otherwise. <a href="https://hashem.faith/gentiles-are-human/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Hashem.Faith</a> addresses these myths with primary-source context—including "Gentiles are human" and "Gentiles are not animals"—showing how the texts have been distorted.</p>', category: 'Jewish beliefs', tags: ['Talmud', 'gentiles', 'goyim', 'dehumanization'], sort_order: 4, sources: [{ label: 'Gentiles are human', url: `${HASHEM}/gentiles-are-human/` }, { label: 'Gentiles are not animals', url: `${HASHEM}/gentiles-are-not-animals/` }] },
  { slug: 'israel-genocide', title: 'Israel Is Committing a Genocide', summary: 'The charge that Israel\'s military actions in Gaza (or elsewhere) constitute genocide.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The charge that Israel is committing "genocide" against Palestinians has been leveled for decades and intensifies during armed conflicts. The term is often used in political rhetoric to condemn Israeli military actions, equate Israel with history\'s worst perpetrators, and isolate Israel internationally.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Calling Israel\'s conduct genocide frames the conflict in the most morally absolute terms and denies any legitimacy to Israeli security concerns. It can also trivialize the legal and historical meaning of genocide and the Holocaust, and is sometimes used to deflect from the actions and goals of groups like Hamas. The charge aligns with the geopolitical and religious aim of some Islamic states and movements to eliminate Israel and to isolate it internationally. It is also promoted by foreign actors—including Iran, Russia, Qatar, and China—as part of information campaigns to divide Americans, turn them against their ally Israel, and weaken Western unity.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Under international law (e.g., the Genocide Convention), genocide requires specific intent to destroy a national, ethnic, racial, or religious group in whole or in part. Israel is fighting Hamas and other armed groups that have attacked it; its stated aim is not to eliminate Palestinians as a people. Tragic civilian casualties and the horrors of war do not by themselves constitute genocide absent that intent. Conflating the Gaza conflict with genocide distorts the term and the Holocaust. See the site\'s Definition of genocide for more.</p>', category: 'Israel', tags: ['Israel', 'Gaza', 'genocide', 'IHRA'], sort_order: 5, sources: [{ label: 'Definition: Genocide', url: null }] },
  { slug: 'israel-discriminates-christians', title: 'Israel Discriminates Against Christians', summary: 'The claim that Israel systematically discriminates against or persecutes Christians.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Accusations that Israel discriminates against or persecutes Christians have appeared in some advocacy and media. They often surface in contexts where Israel is compared to its neighbors or where Christian holy sites and communities in the region are discussed.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The claim is used to portray Israel as uniquely intolerant and to undermine support for Israel. It can be part of a broader narrative that singles out the Jewish state for criticism while downplaying the situation of religious minorities elsewhere in the region. That narrative serves the goal of regimes and movements that seek to wipe Israel off the map for geopolitical or religious reasons, and is often amplified by foreign-funded influence (e.g., Qatar, Iran) to turn Western publics against their ally Israel.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Christian communities in Israel have legal equality and freedom of worship. The Christian population in Israel has grown; Christian holy sites are protected by law and by longstanding arrangements. In contrast, Christians in many neighboring states face severe persecution, displacement, and violence. Israel is one of the few countries in the region where Christian communities have remained and grown. The claim that Israel systematically discriminates against Christians is not supported by the evidence and is often used to single out Israel unfairly.</p>', category: 'Israel', tags: ['Israel', 'Christians', 'religious freedom'], sort_order: 6, sources: [] },
  { slug: 'israel-bans-dna', title: 'Israel Bans DNA Tests', summary: 'The claim that Israel forbids or restricts DNA testing to hide Jewish ancestry or identity.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The claim that Israel "bans" or heavily restricts DNA tests has circulated online, often alongside Khazar or other ancestry conspiracy theories. It suggests that the state prevents people from learning their "real" ancestry to protect a narrative about Jewish identity.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Antisemites and conspiracy theorists use the myth to suggest that Jewish identity or Israeli policy is built on a lie that would be exposed by genetic testing. It implies a cover-up and reinforces Khazar or other "fake Jew" narratives. Denying Jewish indigeneity supports the geopolitical and religious aim of actors who want to eliminate Israel; the myth is also spread by foreign disinformation (e.g., from Iran or Russia) to divide Americans and turn them against Israel and Jews.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Israel does not ban DNA tests. Commercial and medical genetic testing is available in Israel as in many other countries. There are privacy and regulatory frameworks around genetic data, but no general prohibition. The myth is false and is often used to support the Khazar theory or other antisemitic canards about Jewish identity.</p>', category: 'Israel', tags: ['Israel', 'DNA', 'Khazars'], sort_order: 7, sources: [] },
  { slug: 'holocaust-denial', title: 'The Holocaust Didn\'t Happen or Was Exaggerated', summary: 'Holocaust denial or minimization: denying or downplaying the Nazi genocide of six million Jews.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Holocaust denial and minimization emerged among far-right and neo-Nazi circles after World War II. Deniers claim the genocide did not occur, that death tolls were exaggerated, or that gas chambers were not used. Despite overwhelming evidence, denial persists in some online and extremist communities and is illegal in many countries.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Denial serves to rehabilitate Nazism, blame Jews for "lying" about history, and erase the specificity of antisemitic genocide. Minimization ("it wasn\'t that bad") has similar effects. Both are recognized as forms of antisemitism (e.g., IHRA definition). Historically, Christian and nationalist movements have sought to remove or convert Jews; some Christian nationalists today still flirt with these ideas. Holocaust denial has also been promoted by Iran, Russia, and other state actors as part of campaigns to divide Western societies, undermine moral clarity, and turn people against Israel and Jewish communities.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>The Holocaust—the systematic murder of approximately six million Jews by Nazi Germany and its collaborators—is one of the best-documented crimes in history. Evidence includes Nazi documentation, survivor testimony, physical sites (camps, mass graves), and decades of scholarship. Denial and minimization are antisemitic and false. See the site\'s Definition of Holocaust for more.</p>', category: 'Holocaust', tags: ['Holocaust', 'denial', 'Shoah'], sort_order: 8, sources: [{ label: 'Definition: Holocaust', url: null }] },
  { slug: 'israel-9-11', title: 'Israel Did 9/11 Or Knew In Advance', summary: 'The conspiracy that Israel or Jews orchestrated or had foreknowledge of the September 11 attacks.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Soon after the September 11, 2001, attacks, conspiracy theories emerged claiming that Israel, Israeli intelligence, or "the Jews" had orchestrated the attacks or had foreknowledge and allowed them to happen. Variations include claims that Jews were warned to stay away from the World Trade Center or that Israeli agents were seen celebrating. These claims have been repeatedly debunked but persist online.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The conspiracy recycles classic antisemitic tropes: Jews as secretly powerful, malicious, or indifferent to the suffering of others. It deflects blame from the actual perpetrators and feeds into broader narratives of Jewish or Israeli control of events. It also serves the interests of state actors (Iran, Russia, and others) that seek to divide Americans, undermine the U.S.–Israel alliance, and turn the public against their biggest ally in the Middle East—part of a broader foreign-funded effort to turn Americans against each other and against their own strategic interests.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>There is no evidence that Israel or Jews carried out or had advance knowledge of the 9/11 attacks. The 9/11 Commission Report and intelligence investigations attribute the attacks to al-Qaeda. Claims about Israeli foreknowledge or involvement have been investigated and rejected. The conspiracy is baseless and antisemitic.</p>', category: 'Power & control', tags: ['9/11', 'Israel', 'conspiracy'], sort_order: 9, sources: [] },
  { slug: 'jews-control-media', title: 'Jews Control the Media / Banks / Government', summary: 'The classic conspiracy that Jews secretly control major institutions.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The idea that Jews collectively control the media, banks, or government is a centuries-old antisemitic conspiracy. It appeared in European pamphlets and propaganda, in The Protocols of the Elders of Zion (a forgery), and in Nazi ideology. Today it surfaces in coded language about "globalists," "elites," or "the media" when the target is understood to be Jews.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Antisemites use the trope to explain societal problems by blaming a hidden Jewish cabal. It provides a simple, malevolent explanation for complex events and justifies hostility or violence against Jews. It also reinforces the idea that Jews are not legitimate participants in society but secret rulers. The trope has a long history in Christian and nationalist movements that sought to remove, convert, or destroy Jews. Today it is amplified by Christian nationalists in America and by foreign actors (Iran, Russia, Qatar, China) as part of influence campaigns to divide Americans and turn them against their allies, including Israel.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>There is no basis in fact for the claim. Jews are a small minority worldwide with diverse views, occupations, and affiliations. No group "controls" the media, banks, or government in the way the conspiracy suggests. The trope has been used to justify persecution and genocide, including the Holocaust. It is a classic antisemitic conspiracy with no evidence.</p>', category: 'Power & control', tags: ['media', 'banks', 'government', 'control'], sort_order: 10, sources: [] },
  { slug: 'all-jews-wealthy', title: 'All Jews Are Wealthy', summary: 'The stereotype that all or most Jews are rich or financially privileged.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The "wealthy Jew" stereotype has deep roots in Christian Europe, where Jews were often restricted to moneylending and trade while being barred from landownership or guilds. When economic conditions worsened, Jews were blamed and scapegoated. The stereotype persisted through Nazi propaganda ("Jewish capitalism") and into modern conspiracy thinking.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth is used to fuel envy, to blame Jews for economic inequality, and to suggest that Jewish success is illegitimate or exploitative. It often pairs with conspiracy theories about Jewish control of finance or media. Historically it has been used by Christian and nationalist movements to justify exclusion, expropriation, or violence. It is still promoted by some Christian nationalists and by foreign-backed disinformation (Russia, Iran, etc.) to divide Americans and turn them against Jewish communities and Israel.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Jews, like any group, have a range of incomes and circumstances. Many Jews have lived and still live in poverty; Jewish communities include people of all economic backgrounds. The "all Jews are wealthy" idea is a stereotype with no basis in reality. It has been used to justify discrimination, violence, and genocide.</p>', category: 'Power & control', tags: ['stereotype', 'wealth', 'money'], sort_order: 11, sources: [] },
  { slug: 'israel-controls-america', title: 'Israel Controls America Or Has Unjust Influence In It', summary: 'The claim that Israel or "Zionists" dictate U.S. policy or have improper influence.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Accusations that Israel or "Zionists" control U.S. policy have circulated for decades. They often surface in debates over foreign aid, Middle East policy, or lobbying. The claim sometimes uses coded language about "Jewish power" or "dual loyalty" and overlaps with older antisemitic conspiracy tropes.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth is used to explain U.S. support for Israel as the result of secret or illegitimate influence rather than as policy chosen by elected officials. It echoes dual-loyalty canards (that American Jews or officials put Israel ahead of America) and control tropes (that a hidden hand dictates policy). The narrative is central to foreign influence campaigns: Iran, Russia, Qatar, and China have invested in pushing the idea that America is "controlled" by Israel or "Zionists" in order to divide Americans, turn them against their biggest regional ally, and weaken the U.S. from within.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>The United States and Israel are allies with shared strategic and democratic interests; U.S. support for Israel is a matter of public policy, debate, and law. The claim that Israel "controls" America or that support is due to secret Jewish power is an antisemitic conspiracy with no evidence. It ignores the actual reasons for the alliance and falsely implies that support for Israel is illegitimate or coerced.</p>', category: 'Power & control', tags: ['Israel', 'America', 'dual loyalty', 'lobby'], sort_order: 12, sources: [] },
  { slug: 'aipac-foreign', title: 'AIPAC Is a Foreign Organization Compromising Our Politicians', summary: 'The claim that AIPAC is a foreign agent or improperly influences U.S. politics.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>AIPAC (American Israel Public Affairs Committee) was founded in the 1950s as a U.S. advocacy organization focused on the U.S.–Israel relationship. For decades, critics have sometimes demanded that AIPAC or similar groups register under the Foreign Agents Registration Act (FARA), implying they are agents of a foreign government. The demand often overlaps with conspiracy narratives about "Jewish lobby" control.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Framing AIPAC as a "foreign" or illegitimate influence suggests that American support for Israel is not a legitimate choice but the result of a foreign or ethnic lobby. It can echo antisemitic tropes about Jewish power and dual loyalty and deflect from the substantive policy debate. The framing is actively promoted by state actors (Iran, Russia, Qatar, China) as part of efforts to divide Americans, turn them against Israel—America\'s closest ally in the Middle East—and to portray the U.S.–Israel relationship as a conspiracy rather than a strategic choice.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>AIPAC is a U.S. domestic advocacy organization. It does not represent the Israeli government and is not registered as a foreign agent under FARA. U.S. law distinguishes between domestic advocacy and representation of foreign principals. Demands that pro-Israel groups register under FARA often rely on a misapplication of the law and on antisemitic conspiracy framing. <a href="https://hashem.faith/should-aipac-be-registered-under-fara/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Hashem.Faith</a> examines the legal and factual basis for these claims in depth.</p>', category: 'Power & control', tags: ['AIPAC', 'FARA', 'lobby', 'foreign agent'], sort_order: 13, sources: [{ label: 'Should AIPAC be registered under FARA?', url: `${HASHEM}/should-aipac-be-registered-under-fara/` }] },
  { slug: 'jews-defrauding-invading-america', title: 'The Jews Are Defrauding and Invading America', summary: 'The claim that Jews are orchestrating a welfare scam and demographic "invasion" through Haredi enclaves.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Videos and articles have framed rapidly growing ultra-Orthodox (Haredi/Hasidic) communities in the U.S.—such as Lakewood, New Jersey, and Kiryas Joel, New York—as a "Jewish invasion" or as proof that "the Jews" are defrauding America. In early 2026, YouTube creator Tyler Oliveira released highly viewed videos with titles like "I Exposed New Jersey\'s Jewish Invasion…" and "Inside the New York Town Invaded by Welfare-Addicted Jews…." The content visits these enclaves, shows large families, men in daytime Torah study (kollel), and high use of public assistance (Medicaid, SNAP, Section 8), and highlights local tensions over housing, schools, and zoning. Ominous narration and "invasion" language imply a coordinated demographic takeover and a taxpayer scam by "the Jews."</p><h3>Why</h3><p>This framing recycles classic antisemitic stereotypes: Jews as insular parasites leeching off society, or as a hostile group secretly exploiting the system. It presents a conspiracy—coordinated defrauding and "invasion"—rather than a neutral look at policy or local governance. The same pattern has been used against other minority or insular communities (e.g., "Somali invasion" rhetoric about Minneapolis); only the Jewish examples get the explicit "Jewish invasion" / "defrauding" label tied to ethnic and religious identity. It resonates with some Christian nationalists who have historically sought to marginalize, convert, or remove Jews. It also fits the goals of foreign actors (Russia, Iran, etc.) that fund and amplify content designed to divide Americans and turn them against each other and against Jewish communities and Israel.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>There is no evidence of a coordinated Jewish plot to "invade" or defraud America. The percentage of Jews in the neighborhoods under scrutiny has not actually risen; demographic growth in these regions has been driven by Muslim and other foreign-born populations. The "Jewish invasion" framing therefore misframes the situation—it singles out longstanding or stable Jewish communities while ignoring the actual demographic shifts. Residents of these communities are U.S. citizens or lawful residents; they qualify for the same safety-net programs as any other low-income Americans. Eligibility is based on reported income and family size—not fraud. Many Haredi families have low reported income due to emphasis on religious study and large families; some men study full-time temporarily while spouses or family support them, then enter the workforce. Isolated past welfare cases (e.g., in Lakewood) have been repurposed to smear entire communities without proof of systematic wrongdoing. The Anti-Defamation League has stated that such "Jewish invasion" and "welfare scam" narratives "harken back to age-old antisemitic stereotypes." Critics from within or familiar with these communities—including former Kiryas Joel resident Frieda Vizel and advocate Naftuli Moster—have pointed out biased framing: daytime filming overrepresents full-time kollel students, confrontational "gotcha" interviews distort reality, and equating religious study with fraud ignores legal eligibility and varied family arrangements. Broader coverage (e.g., The Forward) notes that this style mirrors prior "invasion" content aimed at other groups, and that local disputes (parking, school funding, zoning) are ordinary governance issues in fast-growing areas, not proof of a cabal. Real policy debates—about sustainability of aid for large families, secular education, or zoning—exist and deserve discussion, but collapsing them into "the Jews are defrauding and invading America" is conspiratorial, unsupported by evidence, and echoes debunked historical myths about "international Jewry" and secret Jewish control.</p>', category: 'Power & control', tags: ['Lakewood', 'Kiryas Joel', 'welfare', 'Haredi', 'antisemitic tropes', 'stereotypes'], sort_order: 14, sources: [{ label: 'ADL on antisemitic stereotypes in "invasion" narratives', url: null }, { label: 'The Forward on framing of Haredi communities', url: null }] },
  { slug: 'jews-killed-jesus', title: 'The Jews Killed Jesus', summary: 'The Jewish deicide myth: the false claim that the Jewish people collectively bear responsibility for the crucifixion of Jesus.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The accusation of "Jewish deicide"—that the Jewish people as a whole bear collective responsibility for the crucifixion of Jesus of Nazareth—is an ancient antisemitic trope. It has been used for centuries to implicate not only first-century Jews but later generations in perpetual guilt, fueling persecution, discrimination, and violence against Jewish communities.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Antisemites use the deicide myth to portray Jews as Christ-killers and to justify hatred or violence. It ignores Jesus\'s Jewish identity and the Jewish origins of Christianity, and deflects from the historical role of Roman authority in capital punishment. For centuries it was used to justify forced conversion, expulsion, and murder of Jews. Some Christian nationalists in America still invoke or tolerate this myth, and a fringe has expressed desire to see Jews removed or converted. The trope is also spread by foreign disinformation to divide Western societies and turn people against Jewish communities and Israel.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Jesus was executed by Roman authorities under Pontius Pilate; the crucifixion was a Roman act, not a collective Jewish crime. The Gospels do not support blaming all Jews—they describe betrayal by specific individuals and a trial in which Pilate ordered the execution. Major Christian denominations have explicitly repudiated the charge: the Catholic Church in <em>Nostra Aetate</em> (1965) stated that the crucifixion "cannot be charged against all the Jews, without distinction, then alive, nor against the Jews of today"; the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America and the Episcopal Church have issued similar repudiations. Historical scholarship and ecclesiastical teaching agree: there is no basis for collective Jewish guilt for the death of Jesus. See <a href="https://hashem.faith/did-the-jews-kill-jesus/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Hashem.Faith</a> for a detailed refutation with sources.</p>', category: 'Jewish beliefs', tags: ['Jesus', 'deicide', 'Christian antisemitism', 'Nostra Aetate'], sort_order: 15, sources: [{ label: 'Did the Jews kill Jesus?', url: `${HASHEM}/did-the-jews-kill-jesus/` }] },
]

// Talmud entries — myths about the Talmud refuted (sources: talmud.faithweb.com "The Real Truth About The Talmud" by Gil Student)
const TALMUD_BASE = 'http://talmud.faithweb.com/articles'
const TALMUD_ENTRIES = [
  { slug: 'real-truth-about-the-talmud', title: 'The Real Truth About The Talmud', summary: 'Why this resource exists: refuting false and malicious allegations about the Talmud.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Anti-Talmud accusations date back to the 13th century when associates of the Inquisition attempted to defame Jews and their religion. The early material compiled by preachers like Raymond Martini and Nicholas Donin remains the basis of many accusations—some true, most false (based on quotations taken out of context), and some total fabrications. Raymond Martini has been proven to have forged quotations. On the internet these old accusations are rehashed; this site corrects the mistakes and puts the true quotes into proper perspective.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Antisemites weaponize fake or distorted Talmud quotes to portray Judaism as hostile to non-Jews. Showing the real truth requires demonstrating in detail how accusations are wrong and intentionally misleading.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Judaism asserts that every human being is created in the image of the Lord and the primacy of integrity and honesty in all dealings. As Rabbi Malkiel Kotler stated: "I strongly repudiate any assertions in the name of Judaism that do not represent and reflect this philosophy."</p><h3>Quotes &amp; context</h3><p>The accusations can be divided into four categories: (1) The Talmud considers itself holier than the Bible; (2) The Talmud contains passages blasphemous against Jesus and Mary; (3) The Talmud has ridiculous and immoral statements; (4) The Talmud has laws that are racist and anti-gentile. The first two are essentially frivolous from a Jewish perspective. The third involves allegory—when properly understood, seemingly silly passages become reasonable. As Dov Zlotnick wrote of Saul Lieberman\'s work: "Rabbinic texts that seem bizarre at first blush can become quite ordinary when properly understood." The fourth is the focus: Jewish law, as contained in the Talmud, treats gentiles with the respect due to a person created in the image of G-d. Their property and lives are honored. The site shows entire passages in original Hebrew/Aramaic and translation, plus how commentators have understood them throughout history. What we demonstrate is that consideration for the Jewish community never relegates those outside it to an inhuman status. Gentiles are always respected and their rights secured.</p>', category: 'About The Talmud', tags: ['Talmud', 'misquotes', 'context'], sort_order: 1, sources: [{ label: 'The Real Truth About The Talmud', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/intro.html` }] },
  { slug: 'what-is-the-talmud', title: 'What Is The Talmud?', summary: 'History and content of the Talmud: Mishnah, Gemara, Halakha, Aggadah.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Jews believe the entire Torah was written by Moses as dictated by G-d. Along with the written text, G-d gave Moses an oral explanation—the Written Torah and the Oral Torah. They complement each other. The Torah often refers to details not in the text (e.g. Deut. 12:21 "You shall slaughter... as I have commanded you"; Tefillin, Tzitzit, Sabbath details). The Oral Torah was transmitted by word of mouth from Moses to Joshua, then to the Elders, Prophets, and the Great Assembly. The Mishnah was codified and handed down word for word. Rabbi Judah the Prince redacted the final Mishnah (finished 188 CE), dividing the Torah into six orders and 63 tractates. The Gemara developed orally for some 300 years; Rav Ashi and his school in Babylonia collected and set it in order (completed 505 CE). Together, the Mishnah and Gemara are the Talmud.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Antisemites treat the Talmud as a single sinister book. Understanding that it is a vast body of law, narrative, and debate helps counter the myth that "the Talmud says" one simple thing.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>The Babylonian Talmud is universally accepted as authoritative. The Talmud contains Halachah (about 90%—definitions, sources, and explanations of law) and Aggadah (about 10%—faith, philosophy, ethics, stories, parables). Aggadah often conveys teachings through parables or riddles; scriptural texts are sometimes understood exegetically. The Talmud is a complement to the Bible that fills in gaps and explains the laws; it is difficult to read because it contains many discussions in the form of proof and disproof, which lend themselves to out-of-context quotes.</p>', category: 'About The Talmud', tags: ['Talmud', 'Mishnah', 'Gemara'], sort_order: 2, sources: [{ label: 'What Is The Talmud?', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/whatis.html` }, { label: 'Judaism (references)', url: null }] },
  { slug: 'talmud-and-bible', title: 'Talmud and Bible', summary: 'Is the Talmud holier than the Bible?', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Critics sometimes claim that Judaism elevates the Talmud above the Hebrew Bible (Tanakh). The claim is used to suggest that Jews follow a "second," secret, or hostile scripture.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Framing the Talmud as "holier" or as replacing the Bible portrays Jewish tradition as deviant or hostile to the Written Torah. In fact, the Talmud is commentary and application of the same Scripture.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>The Talmud is not holier than the Bible. It is the authoritative tradition of interpreting and applying the Written Torah—the same five books of Moses and the Prophets and Writings. Orthodox Judaism holds that the Oral Torah (expressed in the Talmud) was given alongside the Written Torah and transmitted through the sages. Both are integral to Jewish tradition; neither supersedes the other in the way the myth suggests.</p>', category: 'About The Talmud', tags: ['Talmud', 'Bible', 'Torah'], sort_order: 3, sources: [{ label: 'Talmud and Bible', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/bible.html` }] },
  { slug: 'jewish-people-religion-or-race', title: 'Jewish People: Religion or Race?', summary: 'Where do gentiles fit in the Jewish worldview? Is Judaism a religion or a race?', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Jews are an ethnoreligious group: identity is passed through family and community. The Torah and rabbis use the term "goy" in the ancient sense of a people or nation—a group with common history and destiny—not necessarily a territorial state. The question "religion or race?" has been weaponized by antisemites to racialize or delegitimize Jews.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Antisemites sometimes claim that Jewish texts treat non-Jews as a separate, lesser "race." Understanding how Judaism views the Jewish people and other nations helps refute that distortion.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Judaism is a religion and Jews are a people (nation in the traditional sense). Gentile nations fit into the Jewish worldview: the Noahide laws apply to all humanity; righteous gentiles have a share in the world to come. Jewish tradition does not teach that gentiles are inferior or subhuman. The talmud.faithweb.com "Jewish People" and "Gentiles In Judaism" articles address this in detail.</p>', category: 'About The Talmud', tags: ['Judaism', 'gentiles', 'race'], sort_order: 4, sources: [{ label: 'Jewish People', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/judaism.html` }, { label: 'Gentiles In Judaism', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/gentiles.html` }, { label: 'What is a Jew?', url: 'http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jew' }] },
  { slug: 'to-tell-the-truth', title: 'To Tell The Truth', summary: 'Are Jews commanded to lie about the Talmud?', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The accusation quotes "Libbre David 37": that communicating anything to a goy about religious relations would be equal to killing all Jews, and that a Jew "ought to give only a false explanation" of the rabbinic books. The book Libbre David was never mainstream and may not exist; it is strictly prohibited to lie about the contents of the Talmud.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth is used to dismiss any Jewish explanation as inherently dishonest and to justify seeking "secret" versions from antisemitic sources.</p><h3>Quotes &amp; context</h3><p>Authorities are asked: What if a disgruntled man held a gun to a rabbi and demanded "Tell me, are pigs kosher?" <strong>R. Yishayahu HaLevy Horowitz (Shnei Luchot Habrit):</strong> "It is forbidden to change the words of Torah even in times of danger; one must give one\'s life over it." <strong>R. Shlomo Luria (Yam Shel Shlomo):</strong> "We are obligated to give ourselves over and sanctify G-d\'s name... To [lie and] say that one who is innocent is guilty or vice versa is like denying the Torah of Moses." A proof is brought from Talmud Bava Kamma 38a: rabbis taught the truth about the laws to Roman soldiers even though the soldiers might find them offensive. There is a dissenting view (Yad Eliyahu): in a clear and present threat to life, it is better to lie than to have blood shed. But all agree that barring such extreme circumstances it is forbidden to lie about the contents of the Torah or Talmud.</p>', category: 'About The Talmud', tags: ['Talmud', 'lying', 'honesty'], sort_order: 5, sources: [{ label: 'To Tell The Truth', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/lie.html` }] },
  { slug: 'gentiles-are-human', title: 'Gentiles Are Human', summary: 'The Talmud does not consider gentiles to be sub-human.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The accusation cites Bava Mezia 114a–114b: "Only ye are designated men"—implying only Jews are human. The idea runs contrary to fundamental Jewish principles. The Talmud states that gentiles are human; the complicated texts quoted are misinterpreted.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth is used to portray Judaism as inherently hateful and to suggest that Jews view everyone else as lesser.</p><h3>Quotes &amp; context</h3><p><strong>The disputed texts:</strong> Talmud Bava Metzia 114b—Rabbi Shimon ben Yochai said the graves of gentiles do not cause ritual impurity, citing Ezekiel 34:31 ("you [Israel] are called Man (Adam) and gentiles are not called Man (Adam)"). Talmud Keritot 6b uses the same verse regarding anointing oil: only "man" (Adam) is liable; the Talmud learns that in this technical sense only Jews are called Adam. <strong>Contradictory passages:</strong> Talmud Gittin 47a: "The earth He has given to mankind (Bnei Adam)"—gentiles can purchase land; Bnei Adam includes gentiles. Talmud Avodah Zarah 3a: "Even a gentile who engages in the study of Torah is like a Jewish high priest"—from Leviticus 18:5 "which man (HaAdam) shall do... and live." So gentiles are included in "the man." <strong>Resolution:</strong> These are different terms. Adam in the ritual-impurity context refers to the Jewish people as one organic entity (like Adam when he was the only person). Bnei Adam and HaAdam refer to the species; gentiles are obviously members. With regard to ritual impurity and holy oil (uniquely Jewish concepts), the exclusion applies to those not part of the organic Jewish nation. With regard to land or spiritual status, gentiles are included. Gentiles are considered human but not Jewish; the accusations are false.</p>', category: 'Alleged Racism In The Talmud', tags: ['gentiles', 'human', 'dignity'], sort_order: 6, sources: [{ label: 'Gentiles Are Human', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/man.html` }, { label: 'Gentiles Are Human 2', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/man2.html` }] },
  { slug: 'stealing-from-gentiles', title: 'Stealing From Gentiles', summary: 'The Talmud forbids stealing from gentiles.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Critics sometimes claim that the Talmud permits or encourages Jews to steal from non-Jews. The allegation is used to portray Jewish law as morally bankrupt and Jews as permitted to cheat others.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth feeds the stereotype of the dishonest Jew and the idea that Jewish law applies only to dealings with other Jews.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>The Talmud forbids stealing from gentiles. Theft is prohibited regardless of the victim; Jewish law does not permit cheating or stealing from anyone. Talmud.faithweb.com provides the textual context and refutation for this allegation.</p>', category: 'Alleged Racism In The Talmud', tags: ['theft', 'gentiles', 'ethics'], sort_order: 7, sources: [{ label: 'Stealing From Gentiles', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/theft.html` }] },
  { slug: 'paying-gentile-wages', title: "Paying A Gentile's Wages", summary: 'The Talmud prohibits withholding a gentile\'s wages.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Another allegation is that Jewish law permits withholding payment or wages from non-Jewish workers.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The claim is used to suggest that Jews are permitted to exploit or cheat gentiles in business.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>The Talmud prohibits withholding a gentile\'s wages. Paying workers on time and treating them fairly applies to everyone. Talmud.faithweb.com addresses this accusation with sources.</p>', category: 'Alleged Racism In The Talmud', tags: ['wages', 'gentiles', 'ethics'], sort_order: 8, sources: [{ label: "Paying A Gentile's Wages", url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/wages.html` }] },
  { slug: 'tricking-gentiles', title: 'Tricking Gentiles', summary: 'The Talmud forbids lying to gentiles.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>It is sometimes claimed that the Talmud permits or encourages Jews to deceive non-Jews in business or in general.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth reinforces the canard that Jewish ethics allow dishonesty toward gentiles.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>The Talmud forbids lying to gentiles. Honesty in all dealings is a core value; there is no exception for non-Jews. Talmud.faithweb.com refutes this allegation with citations.</p>', category: 'Alleged Racism In The Talmud', tags: ['lying', 'gentiles', 'ethics'], sort_order: 9, sources: [{ label: 'Tricking Gentiles', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/cheat.html` }] },
  { slug: 'killing-gentiles', title: 'Killing Gentiles', summary: 'The Talmud prohibits killing gentiles.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The accusation cites Talmud Sofrim 15:10: "Tob shebe goyyim harog"—"Even the best of the gentiles should all be killed." In no way does the Talmud permit or encourage killing gentiles; it strictly forbids killing anyone, Jew or gentile.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth is used to portray Jews as murderous and Jewish law as sanctioning violence—the opposite of the truth.</p><h3>Quotes &amp; context</h3><p><strong>The disputed passage:</strong> "R. Shimon ben Yochai taught: Kill [even] the good among the gentiles." Without context this seems to advocate genocide. <strong>Full context (Mechilta, on Exodus 14:7):</strong> The Jews have left Egypt; the Egyptians pursue them with chariots. From whom were the chariot animals? Not from Egypt (livestock died in the plague), not from Pharaoh, not from the Jews. Rather from "the Egyptians who feared G-d"—and their livestock caused great hardship for the Jews by being used for chariots. "From here R. Shimon said: Kill [even] the good among the gentiles." He was discussing <em>war</em>: the "good" among the Egyptians were doing battle with the Jews. In battle, do not spare enemy soldiers because they are upstanding people—kill any enemy soldier. That is how post-Talmudic literature has read this (Tosafot, Maimonides). Reading it as an imperative to kill all gentiles is wrong and not how Jewish scholars have ever understood it. Murder of a gentile is forbidden; Maimonides (Hilchot Rotze\'ach 2:11) notes that a Jew who killed a righteous gentile is not executed by the court (per Exodus 21:14 "his fellow") but is punished by Heaven. The prohibition against killing gentiles is explicit in Tosafot, Maimonides, and many other authorities.</p>', category: 'Alleged Racism In The Talmud', tags: ['murder', 'gentiles', 'law'], sort_order: 10, sources: [{ label: 'Killing Gentiles', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/kill.html` }] },
  { slug: 'various-accusations', title: 'Various Accusations', summary: 'Refuting a range of false accusations against the Talmud.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Many other accusations against the Talmud circulate online: that it is racist, immoral, or hostile to non-Jews in myriad specific ways. Often the same tactics appear—quotes out of context, mistranslation, or fabricated passages.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Listing and refuting these systematically shows the pattern of distortion and helps readers recognize similar claims.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Talmud.faithweb.com has a "Various Accusations" page that refutes a range of these claims with scholarly context. The overall message is consistent: the Talmud, read in context, does not teach what antisemites claim.</p>', category: 'Alleged Racism In The Talmud', tags: ['Talmud', 'refutation'], sort_order: 11, sources: [{ label: 'Various Accusations', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/short.html` }] },
  { slug: 'jesus-in-the-talmud', title: 'Jesus In The Talmud', summary: 'What, if anything, does the Talmud say about Jesus?', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Accusations cite insults against Mary, Jesus as bastard/sorcerer, and Gittin 57a that Jesus is "boiling in excrement" in hell. These rely on conflating the biblical figure Balaam with Jesus and on misreading the Talmud\'s character "Yeshu."</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth is spread to portray Jews as hateful of Christianity and to incite discrimination or violence.</p><h3>Quotes &amp; context</h3><p><strong>Balaam is not Jesus:</strong> Sanhedrin 106a—R. Yochanan on Balaam: "In the beginning a prophet, in the end a sorcerer." Rav Papa\'s parable ("she played the harlot with carpenters") explains Balaam\'s descent from prophecy to sorcery; it refers to the biblical Balaam, not Mary. Sifrei and Avot DeRabbi Natan show Balaam as the biblical villain. Mishnah Avot 5:19: "He who possesses... a haughty soul is of the disciples of Balaam the wicked." Historian Louis Ginzberg: "The entire Talmudic-Midrashic literature does not know of any nicknames for Jesus or his disciples." John P. Meier (A Marginal Jew) endorses Johann Maier: no text from the Mishna or early rabbinic material really refers to Jesus. <strong>Yeshu in Gittin 56b–57a:</strong> Onkelos calls up Balaam and Yeshu from the dead. Yeshu\'s punishment is "boiling excrement." Yeshu here is not Jesus of the NT—he is likely a first-century BCE sectarian; the passage distinguishes Balaam and Yeshu. If Yeshu were Jesus, then Balaam in the same passage cannot also be Jesus. The "Jesus in hell" claim is built on misidentification and is not how scholars read the text.</p>', category: 'Christianity In The Talmud', tags: ['Jesus', 'Christianity', 'Talmud'], sort_order: 12, sources: [{ label: 'Jesus In The Talmud', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/jesus.html` }, { label: 'The Jesus Narrative', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/jesusnarr.html` }] },
  { slug: 'blood-libel', title: 'Blood Libel', summary: 'Jews never eat blood; the blood libel is a deadly myth.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The accusation that Jews kidnap and kill Christian children to use their blood in matzah is ludicrous and has led to thousands of murders. Jews are forbidden to kill gentiles (see above) and forbidden to eat ANY blood. Observant Jews take great pains to avoid blood—we bury an animal\'s blood and carefully remove it from meat by washing and salting. Gentiles who do not salt their meat eat more blood than an observant Jew.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The libel portrays Jews as monstrous to justify violence.</p><h3>Quotes &amp; context</h3><p><strong>Torah:</strong> Leviticus 7:26–27: "You shall not consume any blood... Any person who consumes any blood—that soul will be cut off from its people." Leviticus 17:10–14 and Deuteronomy 12:16, 23–25 repeat the prohibition. <strong>Sefer HaChinuch:</strong> Consuming blood "involves acquiring wicked traits." <strong>Tosefta Keritot 2:12:</strong> One who eats an olive\'s worth of blood brings a sin-offering (reaffirmed in Talmud Keritot 21b–22a). <strong>Maimonides (Hilchot Ma\'achalot Assurot 6:1):</strong> "One who eats an olive\'s worth of blood intentionally is cut off... accidentally brings a sin-offering." The Talmud (Chullin 109a, 110b–111a) requires hearts to be split and blood removed, livers broiled so blood comes out. Covering the blood of slaughtered animals is a positive commandment (Maimonides, Hilchot Shechitah 14:1). Meat must be rinsed, salted, and rinsed again to be kosher (Chullin 113a); Shulchan Aruch devotes 10 chapters to salting meat. The blood libel has no basis in Jewish teaching or practice.</p>', category: 'Jewish Holidays', tags: ['blood libel', 'Passover', 'kosher'], sort_order: 13, sources: [{ label: 'Blood Libel', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/blood.html` }] },
  { slug: 'passover-haggadah', title: 'Passover', summary: 'The Passover Haggadah is not racist.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Critics have sometimes claimed that the Passover Seder or Haggadah contains racist or hostile references to non-Jews.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The claim is used to portray a central Jewish ritual as hateful.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>The Passover Haggadah tells the story of the Exodus and celebrates freedom. It is not racist; when it refers to enemies or oppressors, it is in the historical context of the narrative. Talmud.faithweb.com addresses this in the Passover article.</p>', category: 'Jewish Holidays', tags: ['Passover', 'Haggadah', 'Seder'], sort_order: 14, sources: [{ label: 'Passover', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/passover.html` }] },
  { slug: 'kol-nidrei', title: 'Kol Nidrei', summary: 'Does Kol Nidrei give Jews permission to deceive?', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The accusation: "Lying to Gentiles is institutionalized in the Kol Nidre rite, when all oaths that were broken in the preceding year are rendered null and void." A simple reading without Talmudic knowledge would suggest license to lie. Even a little knowledge shows this is totally incorrect.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The myth is used to portray Jews as untrustworthy.</p><h3>Quotes &amp; context</h3><p><strong>Judaism takes vows seriously:</strong> Numbers 30:3—"He shall not desecrate his word; according to whatever comes from his mouth he shall do." The Talmud (Bava Metzia 4:2): "He who exacted punishment from the generation of the Flood... will exact punishment from he who does not stand by his word." Only certain oaths can be nullified—by a court, and only personal vows. <strong>Shulchan Aruch Yoreh Deah 211:4:</strong> "All this [annulling oaths] is said only about a vow or oath that was vowed or sworn for oneself. However, if someone else induced one to vow or swear, this annulment does not help at all." Maimonides (Hilchot Shevuot 6:7): If Reuven induced Shimon to swear, the court does not annul it except before Reuven; "even if the inducer is a child or a gentile" the court does not annul except before him. <strong>Kol Nidrei:</strong> It was originally an annulment of past personal vows before Yom Kippur, or (per Rabbeinu Tam) a pre-existing clause for future personal vows. Either way, no one claims Kol Nidrei exempts anyone from vows that involve others. In business or interpersonal interaction, Kol Nidrei does not provide license to lie or deceive.</p>', category: 'Jewish Holidays', tags: ['Kol Nidrei', 'Yom Kippur', 'vows'], sort_order: 15, sources: [{ label: 'Kol Nidrei', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/kolnidre.html` }] },
  { slug: 'sex-three-year-old', title: 'The Talmud Does Not Permit Sex With A Three Year Old', summary: 'Refuting the horrific allegation that the Talmud permits sexual abuse of children.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>The accusation: "Yebhamot 11b: Sexual intercourse with a little girl is permitted if she is three years of age." The citation is in error (Yevamot 11b has no such passage). The actual discussion is in Ketuvot 11b and concerns dowries, not permitted acts.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The allegation is spread to portray Jewish tradition as morally depraved.</p><h3>Quotes &amp; context</h3><p><strong>The text (Ketuvot 11b):</strong> Rav Yehudah said: A male child who has relations with a female adult causes her to be like one injured with a stick [for purposes of virginity/dowry]. Rava said: An adult male who has relations with a female child has not done anything [for that purpose] because less than three is like sticking a finger into an eyeball [i.e. the hymen is not broken]. The discussion relates to <em>dowry for virgins and non-virgins</em>—when is a woman still considered a virgin for financial/legal purposes? It has nothing to do with what acts are allowed or encouraged. Nowhere does the Talmud permit such behavior. <strong>Maimonides (Hilchot Ishut 1:4):</strong> "Whoever has licentious relations with a woman without marriage bonds is lashed by biblical mandate." Sex outside marriage is strictly forbidden (Maimonides, Shulchan Aruch); so is child abuse. The Talmud is discussing ex post facto classification for dowry, not authorizing any act. Judaism prohibits sexual relations—and even minor touching—outside marriage.</p>', category: 'Immorality In The Talmud', tags: ['sexual morality', 'children', 'Talmud'], sort_order: 16, sources: [{ label: 'The Talmud Does Not Permit Sex With A Three Year Old', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/three.html` }] },
  { slug: 'rabbi-eleazar-prostitutes', title: 'Rabbi Eleazar and the Prostitutes', summary: 'The full story behind a distorted anecdote.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Antisemites sometimes cite a Talmudic story about Rabbi Eleazar and prostitutes to suggest that the Talmud is obscene or that rabbis condone immorality.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>The story is taken out of context to portray Jewish sages as immoral.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>When read in full, the story teaches the opposite: it is about repentance, humility, and the dignity of every person. Talmud.faithweb.com provides "Rabbi Eleazar and the Prostitutes: The Full Story" with context.</p>', category: 'Immorality In The Talmud', tags: ['Aggadah', 'ethics', 'repentance'], sort_order: 17, sources: [{ label: 'Rabbi Eleazar and the Prostitutes', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/eleazar.html` }] },
  { slug: 'in-the-image-of-god', title: '"In The Image Of G-d"', summary: 'Gentiles are created in the image of G-d.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Jewish tradition holds that every human being is created in the image of G-d (Genesis 1:27). This includes all people, not only Jews.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Antisemites claim that the Talmud restricts this idea to Jews or denies it for gentiles. Refuting that is central to showing the real Jewish view.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Gentiles are created in the image of G-d. The Talmud and later authorities affirm the dignity of every human. Talmud.faithweb.com has an article "In The Image Of G-d" that documents this.</p>', category: 'Miscellaneous', tags: ['image of G-d', 'gentiles', 'dignity'], sort_order: 18, sources: [{ label: '"In The Image Of G-d"', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/image.html` }] },
  { slug: 'goy', title: '"Goy"', summary: 'Is "goy" a derogatory term used by Jews about gentiles?', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>It is claimed that "goy" means "animal" and is therefore derogatory. That is not true. "Goy" is Hebrew for nation.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Antisemites claim "goy" is a slur implying Jews view non-Jews with contempt.</p><h3>Quotes &amp; context</h3><p><strong>Biblical usage:</strong> Exodus 19:6—"You shall be to Me a kingdom of priests and a holy <em>nation</em>." The word for nation here, referring to the children of Israel, is "goy." The Jewish nation is called goy throughout the Bible; other nations are called goy/goyim. (See standard Bible lexicons, including Christian sites like Crosswalk.) <strong>Colloquial use:</strong> Non-Jewish nations are called goyim and a member is a goy—descriptive, not inherently derogatory. Leo Rosten (The Joys of Yinglish): Biblical texts called the Hebrews "a holy nation" (goy kadosh); "gentile" is used by Mormons for any non-Mormon (Jews are gentiles to Mormons). Just as some use "Jew" pejoratively ("Jew the price down"), some Jews use "goy" pejoratively after centuries of persecution—but the word itself means nation. The Talmud teaches: "Whether Jew or gentile, man or woman, rich or poor—according to a man\'s deeds does G-d\'s presence rest on him." Respect for others is integral to Judaism.</p>', category: 'Miscellaneous', tags: ['goy', 'language', 'gentiles'], sort_order: 19, sources: [{ label: '"Goy"', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/goy.html` }] },
  { slug: 'ethics-of-the-fathers', title: 'Ethics Of The Fathers', summary: 'The section of the Mishnah dedicated to ethical sayings of the sages.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Pirkei Avot ("Ethics of the Fathers") is a tractate of the Mishnah devoted to ethical maxims and sayings of the rabbinic sages. It is widely studied and quoted.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Showing the Talmud\'s ethical content counters the myth that the Talmud is only hostile or legalistic.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Ethics of the Fathers emphasizes character, humility, justice, and learning. It reflects the same philosophy that every human is created in the image of G-d and that integrity and honesty are paramount. Talmud.faithweb.com has an article on it; it is recommended reading for anyone wanting a sample of Talmudic ethics.</p>', category: 'Miscellaneous', tags: ['Pirkei Avot', 'ethics', 'Mishnah'], sort_order: 20, sources: [{ label: 'Ethics Of The Fathers', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/avot.html` }] },
  { slug: 'schindlers-list', title: "Schindler's List", summary: 'The source of a disputed quotation.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>A quotation sometimes attributed to the Talmud has been circulated in connection with "Schindler\'s List" or Holocaust memory—often in a distorted or false form.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Misattributed or fake Talmud quotes are used to smear Jewish tradition or to suggest that the Talmud teaches something it does not.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Talmud.faithweb.com has an article documenting the source of the disputed quotation and clarifying what the Talmud actually says. When in doubt, check primary sources and scholarly refutations.</p>', category: 'Miscellaneous', tags: ['Schindler\'s List', 'quotation', 'Talmud'], sort_order: 21, sources: [{ label: "Schindler's List", url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/schindler.html` }] },
  { slug: 'recommended-reading', title: 'Recommended Reading', summary: 'Books and links for understanding the Talmud.', body_text: '<h3>History</h3><p>Serious understanding of the Talmud requires access to reliable translations, commentaries, and introductory works. Gil Student\'s site recommends resources for further study.</p><h3>Why</h3><p>Directing readers to sound resources helps them avoid antisemitic or polemical "Talmud exposés" that rely on fake or out-of-context quotes.</p><h3>Facts</h3><p>Talmud.faithweb.com includes a "Recommended Reading" page and a link to "The Complete Idiot\'s Guide to Understanding the Talmud" (Rav Parry). The site also links to related articles and to "A Modern Blood Libel" by Rabbi Dr. Immanuel Jakobovits (refuting Israel Shahak\'s distortions).</p>', category: 'Miscellaneous', tags: ['resources', 'Talmud'], sort_order: 22, sources: [{ label: 'Recommended Reading', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/read.html` }, { label: 'Related Links', url: `${TALMUD_BASE}/links.html` }, { label: 'The Complete Idiot\'s Guide to Understanding the Talmud', url: 'http://www.ravparry.com/' }] },
]

